LEFT JOIN
A LEFT JOIN returns all rows from the left table, and matching rows from the right table. If no match exists, the right table’s columns become NULL

SELECT
  c.customer_id,
  c.name,
  o.order_id,
  o.order_code
FROM customers c
LEFT JOIN orders o
  ON o.customer_id = c.customer_id;
----------------------------------------------------------------------
INNER JOIN
INNER JOIN returns only those rows where there is a matching value in both tables based on a join condition.

SELECT
  c.customer_id,
  c.name,
  COUNT(*) AS orders_count
FROM customers c
INNER JOIN orders o
  ON c.customer_id = o.customer_id
GROUP BY c.customer_id, c.name;

what ever the id's matching from left and right , count only those rows. 

Revenue per customer

SELECT
  c.customer_id,
  c.name,
  SUM(o.total_amount) AS revenue
FROM customers c
INNER JOIN orders o
  ON c.customer_id = o.customer_id
GROUP BY c.customer_id, c.name;
----------------------------------------------------------------------
FULL OUTER JOIN
Retrieves all rows from both tables. If there is a match, it returns the matched rows.

SELECT
  s.student_id,
  s.name,
  p.amount
FROM students s
LEFT JOIN payments p
  ON p.student_id = s.student_id

UNION

SELECT
  p.student_id,
  s.name,
  p.amount
FROM students s
RIGHT JOIN payments p
  ON p.student_id = s.student_id
WHERE s.student_id IS NULL;
----------------------------------------------------------------------
CROSS JOIN
A CROSS JOIN produces the Cartesian product of two tables. 
That means every row from customers pairs with every row from orders, generating m × n rows.
It is rare in everyday CRUD queries, but useful when you want all combinations (e.g., all customer–coupon pairs, all dates × products, generating test grids).

SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM customers c
CROSS JOIN orders o;
----------------------------------------------------------------------
IMPLICIT JOIN
An implicit join is the old-style way of writing joins using a comma-separated FROM clause. The actual matching condition is written in the WHERE clause.

SELECT
  c.customer_id,
  c.name,
  o.order_code,
  o.status
FROM customers c, orders o
WHERE c.customer_id = o.customer_id;

